{
  "texts": [
    "By modeling how structural motifs relate to perceived smell categories, these networks can uncover nonlinear and high-order dependencies that traditional fingerprint-based models may miss.",
    "For instance, GNN-based approaches can predict nuanced olfactory attributes such as floral, woody, or sulfuric profiles based on atomic connectivity and local environments (Sisson et al. 2023).",
    "The integration of GNNs into AI pipelines for both taste and smell holds promise for advancing structure-function understanding.",
    "These models not only improve predictive performance but also offer pathways for explainability, making them suitable for applications in food design, fragrance engineering, and chemosensory health monitoring.",
    "As depicted in Fig. 8, the gustatory process begins with taste molecules interacting with the biological tongue, where taste buds and taste cells collaborate to transmit sensory information to the gustatory cortex."
  ]
}